1. To track the start and end times of seeks in Video.js, you can use the `seeking` and `seeked` events to capture the seek start and end times respectively. However, as you've observed, the `currentTime()` method returns the end time of the seek, not the start time. 

To get the start time of the seek, you can store the current time before the seek starts and then use that stored value when the seek ends. Here's how you can modify your code to achieve this:

```javascript
var trackedPlayer = videojs('pvp-player');
var startTime;

trackedPlayer.on("play", function (e) {
    console.log("Video playback started: " + trackedPlayer.currentTime());
});

trackedPlayer.on("pause", function (e) {
    console.log("Video playback paused: " + trackedPlayer.currentTime());
});

trackedPlayer.on("seeking", function (e) {
    // Store the current time before the seek starts
    startTime = trackedPlayer.currentTime();
    console.log("Video seeking: " + startTime);
});

trackedPlayer.on("seeked", function (e) {
    // Log the end time of the seek
    console.log("Video seek ended: " + trackedPlayer.currentTime());
    // Log the start time of the seek
    console.log("Video seek start: " + startTime);
});

trackedPlayer.on("ended", function (e) {
    console.log("Video playback ended.");
});
```

In this code:
- `startTime` is a variable that stores the current time before the seek starts.
- When the `seeking` event is triggered, the current time is stored in `startTime`.
- When the `seeked` event is triggered, both the end time of the seek (`trackedPlayer.currentTime()`) and the start time (`startTime`) are logged.

This approach ensures that you have both the start and end times of each seek.

